# Shell scripts and git hooks must stay LF on every platform. Git for Windows
# runs hooks via sh, and a CRLF shebang (`#!/usr/bin/env bash\r`) makes the
# kernel look for an interpreter literally named "bash\r" — the hook fails to
# exec and the local version-consistency guard silently no-ops. Pin LF so a
# Windows checkout (even with core.autocrlf=true) keeps these runnable.
*.sh text eol=lf
WxServices/tools/hooks/pre-push text eol=lf

# C# sources are pinned LF to match WxServices/.editorconfig's `end_of_line = lf`
# ([*.cs]). Without a canonical ending the repo accumulated mixed CRLF/LF .cs
# files; once the .editorconfig rule enforces LF, every CRLF file fails the CI
# `dotnet format --verify-no-changes` gate. Pinning here keeps git from
# re-introducing CRLF on a Windows checkout and makes the convention explicit.
# (WX-121)
*.cs text eol=lf
